**Dependency Injection (DI)** is a **design pattern** in which the dependencies (i.e., objects that a class needs to function) are **provided from the outside**, rather than the class creating them itself.

This promotes **loose coupling**, **easier testing**, and **better code maintainability**.

Custom class-

```
namespace Ritesh\_Kaushik\_adding\_middleware.Models;

public class CustomClass  
{  
    
   public  int publicValue { get; set; } \= 100;  
   public void ChangeValue()  
   {  
       publicValue \= 2000;  
   }  
}
```

Controller \-   
```
using System.ComponentModel;  
using System.Diagnostics;  
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;  
using Ritesh\_Kaushik\_adding\_middleware.Models;

namespace Ritesh\_Kaushik\_adding\_middleware.Controllers;

public class HomeController : Controller  
{  
   public readonly CustomClass \_customClass;  
   public readonly CustomClass \_customClass2;  
   private readonly ILogger\<HomeController\> \_logger;

   public HomeController(ILogger\<HomeController\> logger , CustomClass       customClass , CustomClass customClass2)  
   {  
       \_customClass \= customClass;  
       \_customClass2 \= customClass2;  
       \_logger \= logger;  
   }

    
   public IActionResult Index()  
   {  
       \_customClass.ChangeValue();  
        
       *// statement just to print same*  
        
       var customValue1 \= \_customClass.publicValue;  
       var customValue2 \= \_customClass2.publicValue;  
        
        
        
       ViewData\["Value1"\] \= customValue1;  
       ViewData\["Value2"\] \= customValue2;  
       return View();  
   }

   public IActionResult Privacy()  
   {  
       return View();  
   }

   \[ResponseCache(Duration \= 0, Location \= ResponseCacheLocation.**None**, NoStore \= true)\]  
   public IActionResult Error()  
   {  
       return View(new ErrorViewModel { RequestId \= Activity.Current?.Id ?? HttpContext.TraceIdentifier });  
   }  
}
```
Program.cs \-  
```
using Ritesh\_Kaushik\_adding\_middleware;  
using Ritesh\_Kaushik\_adding\_middleware.Models;

var builder \= WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

builder.Services.AddTransient\<CustomClass\>();

*// Add services to the container.*  
builder.Services.AddControllersWithViews();

var app \= builder.Build();

*// Configure the HTTP request pipeline.*  
if (\!app.Environment.IsDevelopment())  
{  
   app.UseExceptionHandler("/Home/Error");  
   *// The default HSTS value is 30 days. You may want to change this for production scenarios, see https://aka.ms/aspnetcore-hsts.*  
   app.UseHsts();  
}

*// app.UseMiddleware\<CustomAuthentication\>();*  
app.UseCustomAuthentication();

app.UseHttpsRedirection();  
app.UseStaticFiles();

app.UseRouting();

app.UseAuthorization();

app.MapControllerRoute(  
   name: "default",  
   pattern: "{controller=Home}/{action=Index}/{id?}");

app.Run();
```

DI container maintains the object.

### **✅ Singleton Lifetime**

* **One instance for the entire application.**  
* It is created **once at application startup** and reused **for every request**, **everywhere** in the app.

### **✅ Scoped Lifetime in .NET Core**

* **One instance per HTTP request.**  
* If you inject `CustomClass` twice within the **same request** (i.e., same tab refresh), both references get the **same instance**.  
* On the **next request** (next tab refresh), a **new instance is created**, and reused within that new request.


### **✅ Transient Lifetime**

* A **new instance is created every time it is injected**, even within the same request.  
* If you inject `CustomClass` twice in one controller or service, **you get two different instances**.  
* Also, a new instance is created on each new request.

Singleton \- Single object created once and used everywhere thats why even in code we created 2 instance and called method to change for one value it showing effect for both.  
(Because behind there is only 1 object.)

Scoped \- Single object created per http request thats why even in code we created 2 instance and called method to change for one value it showing effect for both.  
(Because behind there is only 1 object.)

Transient \- New instance is created every time it is injected means both are separate instance thats why when method called for 1 instance and showing value change for 1
